  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2025 and openly accessible via Zenodo, <em>Archetypometrics, a Pragmateia</em> has attracted over 3,100 downloads and nearly 1,000 views since its release, signaling robust early interest from researchers and practitioners working at the intersection of computational humanities, narrative theory, and data science. While formal citations have yet to accumulate, the download volume places the work in active use well above what might be expected for a preprint of comparable recency.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The paper proposes a framework the authors term \"archetypometrics\" \u2014 an empirically grounded approach to identifying and characterizing the fundamental archetypes of fictional characters. The seven-author team, drawn primarily from the University of Vermont's Computational Story Lab and joined by Timothy R. Tangherlini of the University of California, Berkeley, brings together expertise spanning computational social science, folklore studies, and applied mathematics. The collaboration reflects a sustained research program that has previously examined narrative structure, emotional arcs, and the quantitative dimensions of storytelling. Here, that program turns to character itself, treating the archetype not as a purely literary or psychological construct but as a measurable, dimensional entity amenable to empirical analysis.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The title's use of the Greek term <em>pragmateia</em> \u2014 roughly, a systematic treatise \u2014 signals the authors' ambition: to establish archetypometrics as a coherent methodological field rather than a one-off study. Conceptually, the work sits at the convergence of personality theory, epistemology, and computational narrative science, as reflected in its associated concept profile. The paper is accompanied by openly deposited datasets on Zenodo, and its metadata links to a supplementary story-card resource hosted by the Computational Story Lab, underscoring the team's commitment to reproducibility and community engagement with their underlying materials.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The early usage trajectory is notable for a 2025 preprint. Exceeding 3,100 downloads within a short window after deposit suggests the work has circulated actively across research communities, likely amplified by the Computational Story Lab's established presence and the inherent interdisciplinary appeal of the subject matter. Although formal citation counts remain at zero \u2014 expected given the recency of the deposit \u2014 the attention signals across Substack channels and pilot sources indicate the paper has reached a broad and diverse readership beyond traditional academic venues. Its percentile position within the Zenodo corpus is consistent with this above-average engagement profile.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">From a stewardship standpoint, the work exemplifies current best practices in open scholarship. The article itself is green open access, all supporting datasets are deposited with persistent DOI-based identifiers, and the versioned record structure on Zenodo ensures long-term discoverability. For a field like computational humanities, where reproducibility has historically been uneven, this level of data transparency strengthens the paper's contribution. As the field develops methods to assess and compare character archetypes across large fictional corpora, <em>Archetypometrics</em> offers both a conceptual vocabulary and a reusable empirical infrastructure that subsequent researchers can build upon directly.</p>",
